transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient reports feeling tired and emotionally numb most of the day, describing a lack of emotional response to daily events.

evidence.text: Patient: Hi. Umm… I’m okay, I guess. Still pretty the same, just tired and a bit numb.
Patient: It’s like I go through the day and nothing really makes a difference. I just do what I have to but I don’t feel much—happy, sad, anything. It’s like going through the motions.
Patient: Mostly all day. Sometimes if I’m distracted, like at work, I don’t notice it as much, but when I’m home and there’s nothing happening, that’s when it hits me the most.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient experiences persistent negative thoughts centered on themes of worthlessness and failure.

evidence.text: Patient: Yeah, I wrote some things on my phone… Mostly just stuff like ‘I’m useless’ or ‘I’m letting everyone down.’ I didn’t really know what else to put besides the same things over and over.
Patient: I guess it’s pretty much always about not being good enough, or like I’m failing at everything. It’s all pretty similar, I think.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient finds it difficult to challenge negative self-beliefs and tends to focus on perceived failures rather than positive evidence.

evidence.text: Patient: I tried. Sometimes I’d be like, ‘is it true I’m useless?’ But then I just start listing all the stuff I’ve messed up. I can’t think of any reasons why it isn’t true.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient is able to identify small positive actions, such as making dinner for her mother, but minimizes their significance.

evidence.text: Patient: Umm. I guess I made dinner for my mom one night. It was nothing special, just rice and eggs, but she seemed happy.
Patient: I felt a little better for a bit, I guess, because she smiled and said thank you. But then I thought, it’s just making dinner, that’s nothing.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient reports engaging in some positive coping behaviors, such as listening to music and taking short walks, which provide brief relief from depressive symptoms.

evidence.text: Patient: Yeah, a little. I listened to some old playlists when I was walking. It was okay, like, it helped me not think so much for a bit.
Patient: I went for a couple of walks around the block. Sometimes it’s hard to get going, but I did it, even if they were short.
Patient: Maybe just a tiny bit lighter, but it doesn’t last very long. Mostly I’m still tired.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient experienced an argument with her mother related to job and university responsibilities, which led to feelings of being a disappointment and increased emotional withdrawal.

evidence.text: Patient: I had an argument with my mom. She was asking if I’d applied to any jobs or reached out to the university. I just felt overwhelmed and then she got frustrated. Then I just went to my room.
Patient: Just that I’m a disappointment. I know she’s just trying to help, but I feel like I can’t do what she wants, so I just let her down again.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient finds it difficult to communicate her struggles to her mother due to concerns about causing her mother additional worry.

evidence.text: Patient: It’s hard. She already worries about me. If I tell her I’m struggling, I feel like it just makes things worse for her.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient completed one shift at her restaurant job, felt awkward and made a mistake, but also experienced a brief positive interaction with a customer.

evidence.text: Patient: I did one shift this week. It was okay. I messed up one order but no one seemed mad. Still felt awkward, but I got through it.
Patient: I think I was a little less nervous as the shift went on. One customer actually said thank you and smiled, and that felt okay for a second.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient tends to quickly forget positive experiences and dwell on negative ones.

evidence.text: Patient: Yeah, I kind of forget the good stuff right away, but the mistakes stick with me.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient reports ongoing sleep disturbances, including restlessness, difficulty falling asleep, and waking up frequently or early.

evidence.text: Patient: About the same—still restless, and I wake up a lot. Sometimes I fall asleep late, sometimes I wake up early for no reason.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient notices that increased phone use or rumination makes sleep more difficult, while physical activity such as walking may sometimes improve sleep.

evidence.text: Patient: If I’ve been on my phone a lot or thinking a lot, it’s harder to sleep. Sometimes if I go for a walk, I sleep a bit better—but it’s not always.

evidence.text: Patient: It’s okay. Sometimes I snack more late at night, especially if I can’t sleep.
